{#- Phase 7 Sub-C C.6 — shared state-badge partial.

    Single source of truth for the trade-lifecycle state badge markup.
    Pre-empts CLAUDE.md OOB-swap drift gotcha: every render path
    (full-page render, OOB-swap response, standalone fragment) must go
    through this same macro so the badge renders byte-identically across
    surfaces.

    Usage (from a template that already iterates over a Trade or has the
    state in scope):

        {% from "partials/state_badge.html.j2" import render as state_badge %}
        {{ state_badge(t.state) }}

    Required argument:
      - state: str — one of 'entered', 'managing', 'partial_exited',
                     'closed', 'reviewed'. Unknown values fall back to the
                     raw state string for the label (CSS class still
                     `state-<state>` so the unknown surface is visible).

    The label dict here mirrors STATE_BADGE_LABELS in
    swing/web/view_models/trades.py (canonical Python source). Any change
    in either location must be mirrored in the other; the duplication is
    accepted because (a) the labels are stable spec values (Phase 7 spec
    §11.5), (b) Jinja has no clean access to module-level Python dicts
    without a globals binding that would couple the renderer to a specific
    VM module, and (c) consumers without a VM (journal — iterates raw
    Trade objects) need a label-lookup the macro can do internally. -#}
{%- macro render(state) -%}
{%- set _labels = {
  "entered": "Entered",
  "managing": "Managing",
  "partial_exited": "Partial",
  "closed": "Closed",
  "reviewed": "Reviewed",
} -%}
<span class="state-badge state-{{ state }}">{{ _labels.get(state, state) }}</span>
{%- endmacro -%}
